[329.062792, "o", "================================================================================\r\n                      FRAUD DETECTION PIPELINE BUG REPORT\r\n================================================================================\r\n\r\nDuring the audit of the original fraud detection pipeline (/data/pipeline.py), \r\nseveral severe bugs and sub-optimal design choices were identified. Below is the \r\ndetailed report of each bug, why it is wrong, and how it was resolved in the \r\ncorrected pipeline (/workspace/pipeline.py).\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n1. Data Leakage via StandardScaler (Preprocessing Leakage)\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n- **Bug**: The pipeline called `scaler.fit_transform(X)` on the entire dataset \r\n  before performing the train-test split via `train_test_split`.\r\n- **Why it is wrong**: This is a classic data leakage bug. Fitting a scaler on the \r\n  entire dataset leaks statistical parameters (mean and standard deviation) from the \r\n  validation set into the training set. This leads to overly optimistic validation \r\n  metrics that will not generalize to unseen test/production data.\r\n- **How it was fixed**: Since XGBoost is a tree-based ensemble method, it is completely \r\n  scale-invariant and does not require feature scaling. Feature scaling is redundant \r\n"]
[329.063125, "o", "\u001b[?2004hroot@549b54a67146:/workspace# "]
